<exercise checkit-seed="0002" checkit-slug="FO3" checkit-title="Substitution for First-Order IVPs">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use an appropriate substitution
      to show that all of the following ODEs may be transformed into
      the same linear ODE.
      (Do not fully solve these ODEs.)
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><m>-4 \, t^{3} y^{6} + 5 \, t^{7} y - 5 \, {y'} = 0</m></li>
        <li><m>-30 \, t^{8} - 40 \, t^{7} y = -4 \, t^{3} + 8 \, {y'} + 6</m></li>
        <li><m>y = 5 \, t^{8} y - 4 \, t^{5} + t {y'}</m></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <ol>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = \frac{1}{y^{5}}</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = 6 \, t + 8 \, y</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Let <m>u = \frac{y}{t}</m>.</p></li>
    </ol>
      <p>
          All ODEs transform into
          <m>5 \, t^{7} u + {u'} = 4 \, t^{3}</m>.
      </p>
  </answer>
</exercise>
